[{'account_id': 29100, 'date': '2020-06-03 20:31:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 29100, 'date': '2020-06-03 20:36:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The fact that this template is itself a Jinja template adds some complexity, because you have to understand at what point Kolla-Ansible is rendering things, and where Horizon takes over. I have added some docs to hopefully explain this. I did attempt a solution that overrides the start/end tags for blocks and variables to another value, so the template language was different for the two systems. But, I ran into a problem with Ansible templating. If you have a variable that is itself templated, Ansible applies the new start/end tag style to any variables used in the template, which means they don't really work.

Example: we set some_var="computed_value_from_{{ some_other_var }}"

And in the openrc.sh.template, let's say we pick << and >> to be the new tag syntax.

  #!/usr/bin/env/bash
  export SOME_VAR=<< some_var >>

This will be templated as

  #!/usr/bin/env bash
  export SOME_VAR=computed_value_from_{{ some_other_var }}

And then when Horizon renders it, that variable is not defined, so it will either complain, or just render an empty string:

  #!/usr/bin/env bash
  export SOME_VAR=computed_value_from_

Changing the template tags IMO doesn't make this much easier, and this is a significant downside, so I just opted for documenting how to use raw blocks for this.'}]
